description.value: Papyrus in Hieratic: 'Teaching of Amenemhat' (sheet 2): this particular sheet of the text begins in the middle of the old king's account of how he was attacked in the palace as he slept when the crown prince was not with him. An emblem at the very end of the papyrus names the scribe who wrote this copy and his teacher. It is clear the latter found fault occasionally with his pupils hand; the signs written in the upper margin are the teacher's corrected forms of signs imperfectly copied by the scribe. The sign of the crocodile at the extreme left is a correction of the same sign that appears in the middle bottom line. As is typical of literary texts in hieratic, some groups of signs are written in red ink to indicate section or chapter headings. Also characteristic are the superscript dots called verse points, used to indicate the ends of lines.
